## 1. Get a CentOS 7 node to scan

For this part, you need to bring up a CentOS 7 server that has the standard configuration. Your server also needs:

* an IP address that's reachable from both your workstation and your Chef compliance scanner.
* access to the `root` user account or an account with `sudo` access.
* the ability to connect over SSH.

Although not required, you may find it easiest to bring up your node in the same environment as your Chef compliance scanner. For example, if you're running the Chef compliance scanner on a virtual machine, your node can be a second virtual machine on the same private network.

If you're interested in using Chef to remediate compliance failures, as you'll do in the next tutorial, now's a good time to make sure that your node has port 443 (HTTPS) open for network traffic. This will enable your node to communicate with a Chef server (you'll set up a Chef server in the next tutorial if you don't have one already).

The [Manage a node](/tutorials/manage-a-node/rhel/hosted/get-a-node-to-bootstrap/) tutorial describes some options on how to set up a CentOS 7 node in the cloud or on a virtual machine, as well as how to prepare your node for use with Chef.

Bring up a CentOS 7 system now. In the next step, you set up your node to be connectable using key-based authentication.

[COMMENT] You'll see the username `root` and the IP address 10.1.1.35 in the commands and sample output. Be sure to change these to match your environment.

[END_BOX]

