```

Next, connect to your node over SSH.

```bash
$ ssh root@10.1.1.35
root@10.1.1.35's password:
Last login: Wed Apr 13 19:51:49 2016 from 192.168.77.1
```

Append the contents of your public key to <% fp '~/.ssh/authorized_keys' %>. Then, delete the public key file because it is no longer needed.

```bash
[root@node-1 ~]$ cat ~/.ssh/node1.pub >> ~/.ssh/authorized_keys
[root@node-1 ~]$ rm ~/.ssh/node1.pub
```

Also ensure that password authentication is disabled in <% fp '/etc/ssh/sshd_config' %> on your node. Here's one way to do so:

```bash
# ~
[root@node-1 ~]$ sudo sed -i -e 's/^PasswordAuthentication.*yes/PasswordAuthentication no/g' /etc/ssh/sshd_config
[root@node-1 ~]$ sudo service sshd restart
Redirecting to /bin/systemctl restart  sshd.services
```

Log out of your SSH session.

```bash
[root@node-1 ~]$ logout
Connection to 10.1.1.35 closed.
```

If you're running Linux or Mac OS on your workstation, you need to set permissions so that only the owner can read and write the private key file. Run this command to set those permissions.

```bash
$ chmod 600 ~/.ssh/node1
```

Finally, create a test connection to your node to verify that your node is connectable through key-based authentication.

```bash
$ ssh -i ~/.ssh/node1 root@10.1.1.35
Last login: Fri Apr 15 13:11:09 2016 from 192.168.77.1
```

Keep your connection open for the next step.

