## 3. Configure your node for non-interactive sessions

> In this step, you'll configure the node to only use non-interactive sessions.

The Chef compliance scanner requires a non-interactive session to run compliance scans on a node.

For Red Hat Enterprise Linux based systems, you need to modify the user account's configuration to use non-interactive sessions by default.

Modify the configuration file under <% fp '/etc/sudoers.d' %> for the account you want the Chef compliance scanner to connect through. Here's an example &ndash; replace <% ph 'root' %> with your account name.

```ruby
# /etc/sudoers.d/root
root ALL=(root) NOPASSWD:ALL
Defaults:root !requiretty
```

[COMMENT] For production, you can set up a user account that's reserved specifically for the Chef compliance scanner if you have other accounts that require an interactive session.

If you use a platform such as Chef to manage your production servers, you can automate this modification. [Here's an example Chef recipe](https://github.com/chef/train/blob/master/contrib/fixup_requiretty.rb).

[END_BOX]

